< Review>
This was an..interesting experience. I ordered online for pickup at 6. Online site works well and is easy to follow. I get there 15 minutes earlier than expected, but figured I would see if my food was done. I walked in and it was finished, so I grabbed it and went. Got home, unpacked everything and was missing as roll. I called and the whole phone conversation was stressful. A lot of back and forth since she kept interrupting me, then gave the phone to someone else. I thought she understood that they forgot part of my order, but when my husband came back he said they made him pay for it. I know language barrier can be really frustrating for both sides, but I feel like of they slowed down and let me talk they would have understood what was wrong. The sushi was ok, the ramen bland. I probably would have gone back if the communication wasn't such a hassle, but I don't think I will.<//Review>

<Time>1534122157872</Time><Response>None<//Response><rating>1< /rating><text>This was one of the oddest dining experiences of my life. The food is passable, but not great by any means. The service could really use some improvement. The atmosphere between the owner(?) and employees was downright awkward and there was no priority put on the comfort of the customer. We heard multiple squabbles between employees within ten feet of our table and employees showed no awareness to customers--literally talking about or referencing us like we could not hear. We were asked multiple times what we ordered by the waitress even though we literally gave her a menu with our selections circled, lol. One of the best parts was when the waitress would sit at her little table by the back and yell across the room to different tables: "do you want your check?" A girl came in and sat down and she yelled across the room, "Hun, do you want a water?" A truly hilarious and strange moment, but incredibly awkward to experience first-hand. It sounds like this place is a solid option for late-night sushi and I can see how that would make sense. My one-star review is only meant to inform--I'm sure I didn't experience Jika at its best--but if this saves someone else from an incredibly awkward and unsatisfactory in-person dining experience, then it has done it's job.< /text>< userid>

<Text>Apparently this place is more about delivery than eat-in. Or at least, that was our impression upon our first visit here.
It was 9-ish and a friend and I were strolling the street, we were worried most restaurants would have been closed by that time. So seeing this one advertised to be opened until 1am, we were very glad. Plus, they seemed to have glowing reviews.

The food was okay. Nothing of particular good or bad. A three star experience I'd say.
Not sure if because we ate at 9:30pm so it made that difference.
But what bothered us was the waitress' attitude. She made it rather obvious that she wanted us out of the restaurant as soon as possible, making several trips asking if we were done.
Well I'm sorry that we were not aware maybe the kitchen was understaffed by that time, but your restaurant clearly advertised it to be still open.

<user_name>Sonja Montgomery< /user_name><Resp>None<//Resp><Rate>2</Rate><review>Food was fine. I've only eaten here once, so I'm willing to believe it could be better (or worse).  The service was not great. The waitress appeared to make no effort at all to learn Japanese dish names. On the one hand, the waitress had some great instincts, but on the other hand acted pretty strange--forgetting our order, talking to the chef in a way that I thought was disrespectful, asking me what I ordered so she could correctly bill me. Also, the restaurant should have been cleaner. Maybe I'd be shocked by most industrial kitchens, but we're all in the same room here, and it would be great if I could leave confident that I would not get food poisoning. < Text>
In the midst of a pandemic AND the holidays you'd expect a not so great customer experience, but that's not the case at this FedEx location in Marina Del Rey (on Maxella Ave). The team here is phenomenal - they are organized, helpful, efficient, and most importantly, they are kind.

They get how special it can be to send a friend a gift and they will help organize your package in a way that just opening the box will become an experience for the receiver. They get excited about what you bring in to copy or print because they know that it's something important to you.

There is a sense of community at this location that extends beyond the team and to the customers. Huge thanks to the Maxella Ave FedEx Team, you guys are rockstars!<//Text>

<user_name>Chris Morris</user_name><date>1500174592766< /date>< rate>

< text>
I've been to this store twice and had pretty bad experiences both times.

I saw one employee being rude to several people, though not to me. To one person, I actually saw her visibly turn away from him and roll her eyes after giving him attitude. To another person, she gave him unhelpful answers and acted like he was dumb when he indicated that he didn't quite know how to follow her instructions. She was a terrible helper.

In addition, the printing machines do not work well. The first time I was here, the machine had issues with processing my credit card. It would give me the little 'spinner' for minutes at a time before finally displaying an error. Eventually, after enough attempts, it was able to process my credit card. The machines are very slow and using them takes way longer than it should. What should have been a 15 minute visit ended up taking probably closer to 45 minutes.

The second time I came, I was unable to log in to Google Drive at all. I was presented with a 'spinner' that would spin for several minutes before displaying an error. And the error was the same error that was displayed when I had the credit card problems. So it's not like it was a descriptive error. I tried several times and probably wasted 10-15 minutes. I finally asked an employee and he said that none of the machines were able to connect to Google Drive at the moment due to an issue with upgrading Fedex's network in the office. But there were no signs posted to explain this problem, which is odd. Why wouldn't they have posted signs to let people know that they were having issues with Google Drive.

Both of these issues should not have been issues. Processing credit cards and getting files via Google Drive are pretty core functions for printing documents, especially those that are too big to be emailed as attachments (25 MB limit).

The person who rang me up for my second visit did not speak clearly so it was hard to understand him, as well.<//text>

Beer was great, service was quick, and phone ordering from your table was easy and covid friendly. Menu is currently reduced and the offerings seemed a little over priced for what you get.< /review>

< rating>
4</rating>
<Review>The natural & sculpted beauty that surrounds this place is outstanding and extremely zenful, peaceful, delightful, and completely unexpected!   A small stroll under some trees, a bridge to cross, a med-large pond with large Koi Fish, Lotus Flowers, Lily pads, a running waterfall, a place for musicians to play, etc...  I would go back again to simply enjoy & experience the feelings that the scenary brought out of me.

The drawback for me wasn't even the wait time.  It was not having a server to take our  order.  You order and pay for your meal first and then they bring it out to you - very impersonal and goes against the message the surrounding natural beauty brings out.

There are greeters who greet you with positive energy to take your name and tell you how long the wait time is.  After that,  it gets more distant and frustrating.   There are no mixed drinks here and the food served us was disappointing.

This place is located between large buildings within a Business Park and there is ample parking.</Review><pictures>None</pictures><resp>None< /resp><gmapID>0x80dc0715da411f5b:0xca385eb992acebdb</gmapID></record></dataset><record>

This spot is hands down one of my favorite spots to go to! From their large outdoor patio overlooking a large pond with koi fish and Lilly pads to their fun/inviting atmosphere - plus great food + beer. They have it all!

I've been here a few times and it's always my suggestion when looking for a fun hangout with friends, coworkers after work, or a casual date night with my boyfriend.

From their truffle fries, ahi nachos, mac & cheese, to their blackened mahi tacos and their burgers - you can't go wrong with food either!

They have beer for every taste plus their own hard seltzer, and even some wines.

Shout out to Krista and Laura for their great recommendations on beer and such great service! I'll see you again soon!< /review>

<Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
A great experience with great food. They've implemented a safe way to minimize contact in the days of covid by providing a scannable QR code that will take you to that website and allow you to place your order remotely. The drinks came quickly as did the food. Payment was done through the site as well and it was all very painless. And the food was great too!  The outdoor dining was very serene and lovely and they even helped us with an outdoor heater when the wind got a little cooler. Overall a very pleasant experience.  The Coy pond is awesome.< /Text>

<review>Although there are many Karl Strauss locations throughout SD, we seem to always find ourselves at the Sorrento Valley location more than others.  Located within an office complex, this particular location feels like an oasis away from the city with the Japanese garden (a nice twist on the traditional term "beer garden"), and it's definitely the major selling point for us visiting this location.  Otherwise, the restaurant serves up solid beer food and tapped beers from Karl Strauss.  Plenty of seating for large parties and beer tends to taste better when there's a large group...< /review>< UserId.>

<userid>102727763851376907683< /userid><Rate>5</Rate><name>Shardul Telharkar<//name>< review>
You get vibe of a classy beer-n-wings place the moment you step in the vicinity of Karl Strauss! I loved the way they have designed their entrance besides a pond.
First things first, the food served here is very high quality! I could guess that even a dish as simple as Nachos involved a bunch of ingredients that not all of the restaurants out there would consider adding.
The servants are pretty friendly too! I specially liked the fact that one of us got a complimentary tasting of an additional beer which was sort of another version of what he just had!
For non-alcoholic folks, they have got Root Beer Float which is an amazing option!
The seating by the pond is aptly heated and one may not feel any cold during winters!
Although Karl Strauss puts your meal a little on the expensive side, it is completely justified by their hospitality, ambience and food! I would definitely recommend this place for someone looking to spend quality time eating! :)</review>

<username>Jon Ragatz</username>< user>
101998314907091650348< /user>
< Review>
A tale of two cities.  Beer was fabulously cold and good, all 4 we tried.  Downhill from there.  Went for lunch, first time in years to the Koi Pond location. Of course, new Covid procedures were in place but one has to figure all this out.  We gravitated to a huge menu to study meal options when some burly order taker who hasn't learned how to smile or interact with human beings just stared us down curtly.  I guess we were supposed to know our food choices before seeing the menu.  Fine.  We waited in the beautiful garden area after ordering really enjoying our beers and observing the courteous and hard working wait staff.  And waiting, and waiting, and waiting.  Well over a half hour later, our very disappointing food arrived.  What happened Karl?  Used to be a real treat.  Pastrami sandwich's meat dry, tough and sliced too thick.  Sausages were both bland, if one was a brat, you'd never know it.  Finally, the pretzels were way off, cold, lacking much salt and served with two cups of the same sauce.  Total disappointment except for the brews.  Hardly worth the money, even with the Koi.</Review>

GOOD TIME ! We came here for lunch a while back to catch up with an old friend now living in New York ( pre-covid ). My wife and I had not dined here since 2004 when we were visiting from Australia. It looked like the place has had a makeover since then. It was packed to the rafters but we managed to get a good table for 6 on the high level looking down to the bar. Everyone enjoyed their food but because it was a work day lunch no one was drinking alcohol. Nice atmosphere with the huge Koi pond greeting you at the entrance. Obviously being in the heart of a business district with huge companies like Qualcomm next door keeps the pub pretty flat out !</review>

< review>
Came here on a lunch date with hubby about two months ago and really enjoyed it! The scenery here is stunning. We were lucky to be able to grab a table outside and got to enjoy the peaceful atmosphere and beauty of nature.

Food here is pretty good but options are slightly limited beyond sandwiches, tacos, and pasta.

Our server was very friendly, I can't remember his name but he was very courteous and polite.

We ordered the duck fat pretzels for our appetizer and omg!!! Sooo good! The truffle dipping sauce that came with them was absolutely divine.

For our main meal I ordered the farmhouse burger while hubby had the chipotle pastrami sandwich. He originally wanted the Cioppino but apparently that had been discontinued so he opted for his second favorite food.

My burger was really good but a little on the heavy side. I guess because it had a lot going on. Hubby's pastrami was yummy and juicy, the bread it came on though not so much. I think it was a sourdough ciabatta and that usually takes away from the taste of the food. At least for me anyway. Otherwise everything was great.

I'd definitely come back again! The atmosphere alone is worth it.</review>

< Text>
A tale of two cities.  Beer was fabulously cold and good, all 4 we tried.  Downhill from there.  Went for lunch, first time in years to the Koi Pond location. Of course, new Covid procedures were in place but one has to figure all this out.  We gravitated to a huge menu to study meal options when some burly order taker who hasn't learned how to smile or interact with human beings just stared us down curtly.  I guess we were supposed to know our food choices before seeing the menu.  Fine.  We waited in the beautiful garden area after ordering really enjoying our beers and observing the courteous and hard working wait staff.  And waiting, and waiting, and waiting.  Well over a half hour later, our very disappointing food arrived.  What happened Karl?  Used to be a real treat.  Pastrami sandwich's meat dry, tough and sliced too thick.  Sausages were both bland, if one was a brat, you'd never know it.  Finally, the pretzels were way off, cold, lacking much salt and served with two cups of the same sauce.  Total disappointment except for the brews.  Hardly worth the money, even with the Koi.<//Text>

< Text>
Karl Strauss Sunday brunch is the absolute best thing to happen to my life. Their waffles are phenomenal, and their in-house syrup puts Ms. Butterscotch and Aunt Jemima on the bottom shelf. Plus, who wouldn't be ecstatic to have the opportunity to eat their buffalo chicken in an AYCE setting?

Mimosas are bottomless, beer is good. Karl Strauss is awesome.< /Text>

<rate>5</rate><Text>Came here on a lunch date with hubby about two months ago and really enjoyed it! The scenery here is stunning. We were lucky to be able to grab a table outside and got to enjoy the peaceful atmosphere and beauty of nature.

Food here is pretty good but options are slightly limited beyond sandwiches, tacos, and pasta.

Our server was very friendly, I can't remember his name but he was very courteous and polite.

We ordered the duck fat pretzels for our appetizer and omg!!! Sooo good! The truffle dipping sauce that came with them was absolutely divine.

For our main meal I ordered the farmhouse burger while hubby had the chipotle pastrami sandwich. He originally wanted the Cioppino but apparently that had been discontinued so he opted for his second favorite food.

My burger was really good but a little on the heavy side. I guess because it had a lot going on. Hubby's pastrami was yummy and juicy, the bread it came on though not so much. I think it was a sourdough ciabatta and that usually takes away from the taste of the food. At least for me anyway. Otherwise everything was great.

I'd definitely come back again! The atmosphere alone is worth it.< /Text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNq275j8RLHhtYAFamH5vLWZzSsH-jfpytjszQG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMj4eL82nVHwJ8OPrFdqKv54EvZ-1ekNVLPcID6=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhuHC64vMjQK9nybK9bkqAsav75fphxx7XPLz-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO3sEJ6sdaxE7K-fMLVwfql3hH1LWuYNme3EdYN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>< Response>

Main dishes have also become less innovative.  On top of it,  K has become one of those deceptive places that adds a surcharge to the bill,  instead of just being honest and raising prices.< /Review>

<Time>1557725596989<//Time><UserId.>111113781490230915086< /UserId.><Gmap_id>0x80dc0715da411f5b:0xca385eb992acebdb< /Gmap_id><Resp>None</Resp>< username>
Prakhar Khandelwal</username>
<rating>5<//rating></record></dataset><record>
< GmapID>
0x80dc0715da411f5b:0xca385eb992acebdb<//GmapID>
<time>1557259280901<//time>< Review>
When I'm in need of comfort food, one of my favorite things to do is head to Karl Strauss (or order delivery) to eat Tree Hugger mac n cheese, paired with a Red Trolley ale. The mac n cheese has red peppers and broccoli AND kale nestled among a nest of wonderful cheese sauce, large elbow macaroni, and blanketed by a crispy breadcrumb topping. The presence of these vegetables helps me to feel that I am still reaping nutritional benefits along with the emotional benefits of this meal. The nutty Red Trolley is a perfect counterpoint to the richness of the pasta and has the ability to soothe mind and soul. Am I selling this too hard?
If you are here and thinking of throwing caution to the wind and ordering appetizers too, the duck fat pretzel bites are seriously delicious business. In the past, they had a black garlic fondue which was incredible and I hope it will return.
Last, dessert. I find that a number of breweries skimp on dessert (probably figuring that you've drunk enough of your calories already by that point, rude) but let me tell you about Chocolate on Tap. Brownies. Caramel sauce that had a dangerous liaison with Red Trolley. Vanilla bean ice cream. Whipped cream. It sounds like a variation on a standard dessert offering, right? Wrong. This is it, folks. This is what all those other "brownie with stuff" desserts are trying to be. I've even come here just for this dessert (with another Red Trolley, of course). Worth it every time.< /Review>

<Rate>5</Rate>< text>
Four of us went here to celebrate a birthday because the food and service are always good and it's a lovely setting.

Our server was wonderful with just the right amount of attention. Others also checked in occasionally to make sure we were doing ok.
The food and drinks were all great and served promptly. All the staff were very friendly and attentive.

At the end of our meal our server brought out a very generous and delicious birthday sundae - along with four spoons, yes!
The friend who organized our lunch also brought a cake along with paper plates and forks (she called first to make sure this was allowed). Our server kindly brought out their plates and forks for us to use which was very thoughtful and appreciated.

We went thru the typical (for women) amount of mental gymnastics trying to discreetly calculate how to divide the check 3 ways with of course combinations of cash and credit cards. (The discreet part didn't last long, but the math was correct.) The server was patient throughout this exercise and somehow managed to bring back each check that matched our cards with the correct charge, well done!<//text>

First off, let me just say that our server, Jon, was awesome. He was very knowledgeable and his recommendations were perfect. I've been a few times now and really like this location.

All of the Karl Strauss locations have great beer and pretty consistent food.
What sets this one apart is its great service and atmosphere. The servers are on their game and know how to have a great time!

I believe Karl Strauss bought out this location from a Benihana that wasn't doing too well, which would explain the Japanese influence in setting.

Worth a visit! I only wish they would stay open a bit later on weeknights.< /review>

<user>100750927277108706405<//user><review>I was here on January 2nd, 2017 at around 19:00 after my friend decided to have some beer with dinner. There were plenty of seats as it was a Tuesday. We were seated inside, even though there were plenty of seats outside since it was too cold for my friend. They do have heaters if you do seat outside though. Our server was nice, he guided us to order on our menu and told us what was the special item of the month.
I ordered the home grown burger tonight since I was craving for some beef. My 2 friends who were hungry ordered burgers to. They also ordered buffalo wings and the jalapenos. My other friend drank one beer too until the server kept saying that it is a Tuesday night and smiling while asking for another order of a beer.
The food was great. My beef patty was just right and juicy, the bread was fresh and the veggies were good except for the tomato piece. The tomato piece was fresh, but I did not like the piece that came with the sandwich because it was a hard piece. The fries were crunchy. My friend who had the chips also liked it. I tried a piece and it was crispy. I also liked the buffalo chicken appetizer since it was boneless. The jalapeno was good tasting, had cheese inside, but pricey for what it is. It is almost as much as a burger. My friend liked 2 out of the 3 beers he tried.
The service here was great. They refilled our water and cleared the appetizer plates in time to make room for the burgers. They even gave us a whole jug of water which we did not use and there were free beer samples that they offered tonight. But my friend and I decided to pass on free beer because for me, I rarely consume alcohol and my friend had a New Year's resolution of not drinking beer. I can say the beer is pretty good since most of my friends who have been here liked it.
This is a great place for people to relax after work, eat good dinner and sip on some beers. But for people like me who do not drink, I do find prices to be a bit on the high end. My homegrown burger cost me $14.95 and the Jalapeno appetizer cost almost $10. I had a great experience here and recommend it for those who want a drink on Thursday-Saturday night.<//review>< Name>
nn viekie<//Name>

< text>
We come here quite often because it's so close to work.  Anyway, I have yet to find a dish I don't like here and the beers are pretty decent.  Everything is pretty good for a brewery/restaurant.  The Japanese garden/pond really elevates the atmosphere.  Never had an issue with the service either.

The place can be a tad tricky to find (located within an industrial park) but just follow the signs!  Warning:  It can get very busy here even on the weekdays.  There are very few bars in this area so everyone comes here for happy hour.</text>

We came here for lunch today to catch up with an old friend now living in New York. My wife and I had not dined here since 2004 when we were visiting from Australia. It looks like the place has had a makeover since then. It was packed to the rafters but we managed to get a good table for 6 on the high level looking down to the bar. Everyone enjoyed their food but because it was a work day lunch no one was drinking alcohol. Nice atmosphere with the huge Koi pond greeting you at the entrance. Obviously being in the heart of a business district with huge companies like Qualcomm next door keeps the pub pretty flat out.</text>

< gmapID>
0x80dc0715da411f5b:0xca385eb992acebdb< /gmapID>
< Review>
A great spot for dinner or drinks.

The food: The menu is big and you can get anything from a salad, to burgers, to fish and chips. It is your basic gastro-pub menu. Something for everyone.

The beer: They only serve Karl Strauss beers. You won't find as many of the RnD stuff that you'll find at their PB location, but there are plenty of great beers to choose form. I usually opt for the Mosaic session ale.

The location: Its crowded, and there is usually a line. The place itself recently got a makeover that added more tables and a more open layout. We usually ask to sit next to the pond so we can enjoy the weather and watch the fish.< /Review>

< text>
It's colloquially referred to by the Qualcomm employees that visit it often as "Building K", and has a great happy hour on weekdays.  Their food is great and the service never disappoints either.  In terms of craft beers, these guys are on point, and their style isn't just the generally over-hopped San Diego norm.  The Japanese style gardens surrounding this place are really nice as well and make it a great destination to book for special events like wedding receptions.</text>

OMG what a great "hidden treasure"   Great service from my phone call before driving up to checking on hours and wait time, to check in and tableside servers keeping my Mimosa glass to the brim and musing about the great spread.

< review>
Been to too many breweries, good beer and food but service is by far the worst when compared to ballast point and stone. For the past 4 times I've visited, I've felt nothing but bad service. In other words, ignored.
On this last visit.

1) they got my order wrong. I ordered a blta with extra meat (chicken)
2) they took the salad back and brought back chicken that was not even warmed up but pre grilled and chilled. I was definitely expecting something a bit more toasty to match the pork belly on the salad.
3) lastly I mainly felt ignored. They were rarely any servers in our area (the dock) and I felt like me and my fiance had to forcefully ask other servers to place our orders. We spoke to 4 different employees who served us tonight.

I am seriously going to stop giving this place a chance and continue to go to the places that truly appreciate their customers with excellent service. Bye bye Karl Straus Sorrento Valley ðŸ‘‹ðŸ‘‹</review>

Been to too many breweries, good beer and food but service is by far the worst when compared to ballast point and stone. For the past 4 times I've visited, I've felt nothing but bad service. In other words, ignored.
On this last visit.

1) they got my order wrong. I ordered a blta with extra meat (chicken)
2) they took the salad back and brought back chicken that was not even warmed up but pre grilled and chilled. I was definitely expecting something a bit more toasty to match the pork belly on the salad.
3) lastly I mainly felt ignored. They were rarely any servers in our area (the dock) and I felt like me and my fiance had to forcefully ask other servers to place our orders. We spoke to 4 different employees who served us tonight.

<user_id>114685023988069049279<//user_id><username>Brian S</username><Time>1478575480905<//Time>< rate>
2< /rate>
<Review>How can I put this nicely: KSBG is Stone's ugly older sister. Do you enjoy second-rate "craft" beer? Do you relish being constantly told to move, just because you had the audacity to order beer (and not food) AT A BREWERY? If so, this is the place for you! Unlike at Stone, where you can actually buy a pint and walk around the garden, at KSBG you're a virtual leper unless you wait for a table and order food. The famed Japanese garden consists of little more than a pond and a decorated hillside, and you'll most likely be stuck sitting inside their nondescript restaurant, or standing uncomfortably in the spaces between tables near their bar. I've got to hand it to Karl though, he really knows how to pack in the North County office park folk. Overall, the experience is about as much fun as crashing someone else's office happy hour.< /Review>< pics>
None<//pics>

<Name>Pradeep Mohanannair<//Name><gmap_id>0x80dc0715da411f5b:0xca385eb992acebdb<//gmap_id><Text>Karl Strauss (Scanton Road)
AKA "Building K" affectionately by Qualcommers

The naming reason for Building K is, Qualcomm has 50+ buildings around Sorrento Valley and they are named with alphabets like Q, A, B, W etc,  this is regular happy hour place for Qualcommers and hence this is also considered as one of the building of Qualcomm and we affectionately call Karls Strauss as Building K

Beer Choices: Plenty , ~ 15 taps
*** Top 5 Beers (No-Particular Order) ***
Red Trolley (the most consumed liquid next to water here)
Mosaic IPA
Wreck Alley (Imperial Stout)
WindanSea (Heifenweiser Wheat Beer)
Small Batch (Dark n Sour)
And their other seasonal like Off the Rails (Hoppy version of Red Trolley)

***Ambiance***
Indoor, you will be beer-high just standing there. Beer is in the air, awesome. Lot of TVs with Bar stool and  Restaurant style eatings.
Outdoor, Ambiance with a lovely pond with large Koi Fishes

***Prices***
Tasters: beer flight for $5. (choose any 4 on the menu)
Beer : $6 16 oz acerage
Buffet: $26
Entrees ~$18 average
Burgers range from $11-15

***Food***
Even without Beer, this place is awesome for Food lovers, I am listing few of the best
Appetizers: There Nachos are out of the world, spinach artichoke dip, buffalo wings, Asada Fries, Pita, Bread and Hummus and Calamari rings all are highly recommended

Salad: Ahi Poke Salad

Entrees : baja shrimp skillet, Tacos and Blackened salmon,  Spicy chicken sandwich (average and safe) Fish and chips

Veg: tofu curry, Veg burger,

Champagne brunch buffet on the weekends
Brunch buffet was ~$30/person. The buffet comes with either 1 glass of beer, a flight of 4 beers/ Bottomless mimosas.
Brunch buffet highlights:
Omelet station, Mini waffles, chicken wings, Ahi poke, Smoked salmon, Baked salmon with mango salsa and Plenty of desserts

***Try this***
Outside seating along with pond and High Patio seating for the View.
Ask for Bumper stickers.
Champagne brunch buffet on the weekends

***Highs***
Ambiance with a lovely pond with large Koi Fishes
Full food menu with Great appetizers
Very Friendly service
Neat Happy hour pricing
Proximity for Qualcommers

***Lows***
Long wait and super crowded.
Parking might get over crowded
Expensive side on the food

Tip: Make Reservation<//Text><UserId.>110239633349088513540< /UserId.><Rating>4</Rating></record></dataset><record>

<userid>116870086372709660834</userid><username>ricky wu<//username><time>1447694079901<//time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
This place is like an oasis from urban life. Within a seemingly random office space estate, hides a beautiful Japanese themed architecture. There is a large koi pond. If you sit next to it, be careful about losing things into the pond. There was evidence of forks, knives, etc on the pond floor.

Food: we came for the 25 dollar all you can eat brunch. Scheduling said we wouldn't be able to get a table because reservations were full (this was over the phone). We showed up anyway and were seated right away. The breakfast buffet included an omelette bar, various international breakfast foods, desserts, and a prime rib station. All of the food was delicious.

Beer: included in the 25 dollar deal was a choice of beer flight, bottomless mimosas, 2 beer-mosas, or non-alcoholic beverages. I had the beer flight. It included their Oktoberfest, Windansea, red trolley ale (bonus), and a couple others that were too hoppy for my tastes. The 3 that I named were absolutely delicious and paired well with mostly all the breakfast foods, especially the meats. I went and bought some red trolley afterwards. My girlfriend ordered the beer-mosas which turned out to be an excellent choice. I believe they mixed the Windansea and a mimosa.

All of this was amazing. Come, eat, drink, enjoy!<//review>

< Review>
Solid selection of beer and even a couple hard seltzer. Everything was open and easy to navigate in covid times. Staff was very helpful. Location and scenery was surprisingly awesome. Food was somewhat innovative and inclusive but still falls in the average category. Overall a great experience that I look forward to trying again after covid lockdown.</Review>
